        <page n="01" image="va.au.rv.1860.02.24.01">
            <div type="a">
                <column>6</column>
                <head>Cotton and American Slavery</head>
                <origin>London Times</origin>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>The London Times discusses the importance of cotton to English
                    manufacturing and criticizes the Anti-Slavery Society for failing to recognize
                    that ending American slavery will severely disrupt the British
                economy.</summary>
            </div>
            <pageNote>Gov. Letcher's annual message.</pageNote>
        </page>
        <page n="02" image="va.au.rv.1860.02.24.02">
            <div type="a">
                <column>1</column>
                <head>The Southern Conference</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>The Vindicator argues that most Virginians, irrespective of party, support
                    the proposal to attend a Southern Conference. The paper argues that the
                    Conference is not a disunion movement per se. The cotton states support
                    secession, so Virginia needs to attend the Southern Conference to provide
                    "moderate and conservative counsels" to "her more hot-headed sisters."</summary>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>2</column>
                <head/>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Commentary on article from London Times reprinted on page 1. The Vindicator
                    points out that the North benefits from slavery, just as the British
                do.</summary>
            </div>
